# Architecture

> Structural decisions for the Agents Relay Orchestration module.


## Architecture

---

## A1 Relay Orchestrator Architecture
**Status:** draft
**Depends on:** G2

An LLM-based orchestrator would consume tokens for routing decisions, violating G3's token-efficiency mandate. It would also introduce non-determinism into flow execution. A deterministic state machine in Rust provides zero-token coordination, predictable routing, and compile-time safety.

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph "Orchestrator (Rust)"
        O[PipelineEngine]
        F[FlowSpec Parser]
        H[Handoff Manager]
        C[Checkpoint Manager]
        B[Budget Tracker]
    end
    subgraph "Agent Turn"
        A[AgentInstance]
        T[ToolRegistry Filter]
        D[Multi-Provider Dispatch]
    end
    subgraph "AI Providers"
        AP[Anthropic]
        OP[OpenAI]
        LP[Local/Ollama]
    end
    subgraph "Specs (Ledger)"
        L[Jades / Ledger]
    end
    subgraph "Persistence"
        P[Checkpoint Store]
        R[Run Store]
        CS[Config Store]
    end

    O -->|parse| F
    O -->|generate| H
    O -->|save/load| C
    O -->|track| B
    O -->|spawn from config| A
    A -->|filtered| T
    A -->|chat via| D
    D -->|route| AP
    D -->|route| OP
    D -->|route| LP
    A -->|read/write| L
    C -->|serialize| P
    O -->|persist| R
    O -->|load configs| CS
```

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| Deterministic Rust orchestrator | Zero token cost, predictable, fast, type-safe | Cannot adapt to novel flow patterns without code change |
| LLM-based orchestrator | Flexible, natural language flow definitions | Token cost per routing decision, non-deterministic, harder to test |
| Hybrid (LLM plans, Rust executes) | Flexibility + determinism | More complex, LLM still needed for plan generation |

- Positive: Flow execution is deterministic and unit-testable.
- Positive: No token spend on coordination.
- Negative: New flow patterns (e.g., conditional routing based on spec content) require code changes to `PipelineEngine`.
- Mitigation: FlowSpec supports `branch`, `loop`, and `on_fail` primitives that cover 95% of use cases.


---

## A2 Agent Instance Lifecycle
**Status:** draft
**Depends on:** G1, G2

Long-lived agent processes would accumulate context and state, defeating the token-efficiency goal. By spawning fresh instances per step, each agent starts with a clean, minimal context window. This also simplifies crash recovery — no need to restore agent memory, only the checkpoint.

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> Spawning: Orchestrator starts step
    Spawning --> ConfigResolving: Look up AgentConfig by profession
    ConfigResolving --> Running: Soul + Specs + Handoff + resolved Model loaded
    Running --> ToolCall: Agent invokes tool
    ToolCall --> Running: Tool result appended
    Running --> HandoffComplete: Agent calls handoff tool
    Running --> BudgetExceeded: Token limit reached
    Running --> Error: Panic / API failure
    Error --> Fallback: Try fallback model from ApiSource
    Fallback --> Running: Retry with fallback model
    Fallback --> Failed: All fallbacks exhausted
    HandoffComplete --> [*]: Instance dropped, checkpoint saved
    BudgetExceeded --> [*]: Forced handoff, budget note added
    Failed --> [*]: Run marked Failed, human notified
```

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| Ephemeral per-step instances | Minimal context, easy recovery, cheap | Agent cannot learn across turns within a step |
| Long-lived instances with context window | Agent remembers earlier turns | Context grows, recovery harder, more tokens |
| Persistent agent processes with memory | Cross-run learning possible | Complex state management, not needed for relay |

- Positive: Maximum token efficiency.
- Positive: Crash recovery is trivial — just re-spawn from checkpoint.
- Negative: If an agent needs 5 turns to complete, each turn re-loads the same Soul + Specs. However, this is cheaper than maintaining a growing context.


---

## A3 Checkpoint & State Persistence
**Status:** draft
**Depends on:** G4

JSON provides human-readable, version-controllable checkpoints. Git auto-commits provide a robust file-level rollback mechanism that integrates with existing developer workflows. The Ledger is embedded (not referenced) to ensure self-contained checkpoints.

```mermaid
graph LR
    A[Handoff Triggered] --> B[Capture File Manifest]
    B --> C[Git Commit or Diff]
    C --> D[Serialize Ledger]
    D --> E[Write Handoff Document]
    E --> F[Write Checkpoint JSON]
    F --> G[Update Run Store]
```

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| JSON + git | Human-readable, git-native rollback, simple | Large checkpoints for big projects |
| SQLite + binary blobs | Compact, queryable | Harder to inspect, git-unfriendly |
| Content-addressed store (IPFS-style) | Deduplication, immutable | Overkill for local orchestration |

- Positive: Checkpoints can be inspected with `cat` or `jq`.
- Positive: Rollback uses standard git commands.
- Negative: Large projects may produce multi-MB checkpoint files.
- Mitigation: File manifest stores hashes, not contents. Only changed files are diffed.

---

## A4 Boss-First Execution Architecture
**Status:** approved
**Depends on:** G6

The default workflow for AI assistants requires human approval at every step. This treats the human as a peer reviewer. AutoForge treats the human as a boss who delegates and expects results. GSD mode shifts the default from "ask for permission" to "ask for forgiveness" — the AI executes autonomously and only interrupts the boss when blocked.

```mermaid
graph LR
    A[Boss Request] --> B{Assistant classify}
    B -->|QUESTION| C[Answer & Stop]
    B -->|DIRECT| D[Coder]
    B -->|NEW_GOAL| E[Advisor]
    E -->|GSD| F{GoalGate}
    F -->|Auto| G[Architect]
    G --> H[Planner]
    H --> I[Coder]
    I --> J{Tests pass?}
    J -->|No| I
    J -->|Yes| K[Reviewer]
    K --> L[Documenter]
    L --> M[Report to Boss]
    F -->|Check mode| N[Human Review]
    N --> G
```

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| GSD default, Check opt-in | Boss is productive; AI does the work | AI may build wrong thing confidently |
| Check default, GSD opt-in | Boss reviews every step | Boss is a bottleneck; loses async value |
| Hybrid (GSD with auto-drifts) | Balance of speed and safety | More complex routing logic |

- Positive: Boss gives one order, receives one report.
- Positive: Reviewer acts as internal QA, not an external gate.
- Negative: If Advisor writes bad Goals, everything downstream is wrong.
- Mitigation: GoalGate is the one required human gate in GSD mode. Advisor uses medium/strong model.


---

## A5 Frontend Composable State Architecture
**Status:** implemented
**Depends on:** G8

An LLM-based orchestrator would consume tokens for routing decisions, violating G3's token-efficiency mandate. It would also introduce non-determinism into flow execution. A deterministic state machine in Rust provides zero-token coordination, predictable routing, and compile-time safety.

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph "Frontend Composables"
        F[useForge.ts]
        R[useRelay.ts]
        S[useSpecs.ts]
        G[useGateInbox.ts]
        I[useItemRelations.ts]
        AS[useApiSources.ts]
        AC[useAgentConfigs.ts]
        P[useProject.ts]
    end
    subgraph "Vue Components"
        C[ChatView]
        V[SpecsView]
        L[RelayView]
        AV[ApiSourcesView]
        AE[AgentsConfigView]
    end

    F -->|session gates| G
    R -->|run gates| G
    G -->|renders| C
    R -->|invalidates| S
    S -->|finds item| I
    I -->|enriches| V
    R -->|uses agent configs| AC
    AC -->|reads api sources| AS
    F -->|uses api sources| AS
    AS -->|renders| AV
    AC -->|renders| AE
```

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| Vue 3 Composables (singleton refs) | Zero boilerplate, matches existing code, tree-shakable, direct cross-import | No time-travel debugging; state is implicit |
| Pinia global store | DevTools support, mutations traceable | More boilerplate, refactor cost for existing composables |
| Redux/Vuex | Time-travel, predictable state updates | Massive overhead for a Vue 3 project |

- Positive: `useGateInbox` can import `useRelay` and `useForge` directly to listen for gate events without event bus indirection.
- Negative: Composable cross-imports create a soft dependency graph that is not explicitly declared.
- Mitigation: Document cross-cutting concerns in the Architecture ADR; avoid circular imports by keeping `useGateInbox` as the central hub.


---

## A6 Chat Ephemeral Chrome Architecture
**Status:** implemented
**Depends on:** G8

Persisting cross-session gate messages into the current session's `ForgeMessage` array would pollute the chat audit trail with foreign conversation state. The backend `ForgeMessage` schema has no `gate` role and should not be extended for UI chrome.


```mermaid
graph LR
    A[useGateInbox.active] -->|v-if| B[SecretaryMessage.vue]
    C[messages: ForgeMessage[]] -->|v-for| D[ChatMessage.vue]
    B -.->|ephemeral| E[Chat DOM]
    D -->|persisted| E
```

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| Ephemeral Vue components (chosen) | Clean backend schema, no migration, chat history is accurate | Secretary messages disappear on refresh unless inbox is hydrated |
| Persisted `system` role messages | Survives refresh, simple rendering | Pollutes session history with external state; backend schema change |
| Separate "inbox" message stream | Clean separation | Complex UI: two message streams to render and scroll |

- Positive: Backend `ForgeMessage` schema unchanged.
- Positive: Chat history export contains only this session's conversation.
- Negative: Page refresh loses the visual secretary message (but not the gate state, which is in `useGateInbox` and can be rehydrated).
- Mitigation: On mount, `useGateInbox` fetches `/api/forge/gates/pending` and re-renders any active gates.


---

## A7 API Source & Multi-Provider Architecture
**Status:** proposed
**Depends on:** G13

A single hardcoded provider (Claude only) limits agent flexibility and cost optimization. Agents in different roles have different cognitive requirements — a routing Assistant needs a cheap/fast model, while an Architect needs a strong reasoning model. Multi-provider support enables per-agent model selection from any configured API source.

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph "Config Layer"
        CF[config.rs] -->|load| AS[ApiSource Store]
        CF -->|load| AC[AgentConfig Store]
    end
    subgraph "Provider Dispatch"
        DP[dispatch_chat] --> AP[Anthropic Provider]
        DP --> OP[OpenAI Provider]
        DP --> LP[Local/Ollama Provider]
    end
    subgraph "Pipeline"
        PE[PipelineEngine] -->|resolve| RC[RelayRegistry]
        RC -->|spawn from| AC
        AC -->|uses| AS
        AS -->|routes via| DP
    end

    PE -->|step| AG[AgentInstance]
    AG -->|chat via| DP
```

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| Multi-provider dispatcher with ApiSource configs | Per-agent model selection, cost optimization, provider flexibility | More complex AI dispatch layer, multiple SSE format parsers |
| Single provider with model tiers only | Simpler implementation | Locked into one provider, no fallback across providers |
| Runtime model registry (no config UI) | No UI needed | Users cannot manage API keys or discover models |

- Positive: Each agent can use the optimal provider + model for its task.
- Positive: First-startup auto-detection finds existing keys — zero config for most users.
- Positive: Test Connection endpoint validates setup before running pipelines.
- Negative: Three different SSE parsing paths (Anthropic, OpenAI, Local) must be maintained.
- Mitigation: OpenAI and Local share the same `/v1/chat/completions` format; only Anthropic differs.

### Key Architecture Decisions





```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph "New Composables"
        UA[useApiSources.ts]
        UAC[useAgentConfigs.ts]
    end
    subgraph "Existing Composables"
        UF[useForge.ts]
        UR[useRelay.ts]
        US[useSpecs.ts]
        UG[useGateInbox.ts]
    end

    UAC -->|reads| UA
    UR -->|uses| UAC
    UF -->|uses| UA
```

