## A8 Unified Provider & Runtime Architecture
**Status:** done
**Depends on:** G14, G15

Two separate AI provider implementations (ai.rs for simple chat, forge/ai.rs for tool-enabled chat) created maintenance burden and duplicated SSE parsing logic. The unified provider/ module consolidates both into a single ClaudeProvider with two streaming modes, backed by a robust incremental SSE parser ported from auto-code-rs.

```mermaid
graph TB
    subgraph "Entry Points"
        CLI[CLI REPL] -->|chat_turn| P[ClaudeProvider]
        WEB[Web API] -->|chat_stream| P
        RLY[Relay Turn] -->|chat_turn| P
    end
    subgraph "Provider Layer"
        P --> SSE[SseParser]
        P --> CFG[load_api_config]
    end
    subgraph "Runtime"
        CM[ContextManager]
        SES[Session Persistence]
        PM[PermissionPolicy]
    end
    subgraph "Tools"
        TR[ToolRegistry]
        TE[ToolError]
    end

    CLI --> CM
    CLI --> TR
    CLI --> PM
    WEB --> TR
    RLY --> TR
```

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| Unified provider/ module (chosen) | Single source of truth, DRY, easy to add providers | All consumers must migrate imports |
| Keep ai.rs + forge/ai.rs separate | No migration needed | Duplicate SSE logic, divergent error handling |
| Trait-based provider abstraction | Pluggable providers | Over-engineered for single-provider use case |

- Positive: Single SSE parser handles both `\r\n\r\n` and `\n\n` frame delimiters.
- Positive: ToolError enum provides structured error classification instead of raw String.
- Positive: Runtime infrastructure (ContextManager, Session, PermissionPolicy) available to both CLI and web modes.
- Negative: OpenAI provider not yet ported (only Claude supported currently).
- Mitigation: provider/ module is structured to accept additional providers without architectural changes.

---

## A9 Chat-Turn Agent Handoff Architecture
**Status:** proposed
**Depends on:** G16, G17

The relay pipeline (A1) uses formal `HandoffDocument` generation between steps, but the free-form chat flow has no handoff mechanism. The assistant (Nicole) classifies user intent but cannot act on that classification — she answers everything herself with all tools. The bring-in tool bridges this gap by letting Nicole invoke another agent mid-conversation, passing structured context so the receiving agent doesn't ask the user to repeat.

```mermaid
graph LR
    U[User Message] --> N[Nicole: Assistant]
    N -->|classify| D{Intent?}
    D -->|QUESTION| AN[Nicole answers]
    D -->|DIRECT| AN
    D -->|NEW_GOAL| B[bring_in tool]
    D -->|REQ_UPDATE| B
    B -->|handoff note| I[Isaac: Advisor]
    I -->|continue chat| U
    B -->|handoff note| ASH[Ash: Coder]
    ASH -->|continue chat| U
```

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|
| bring_in tool with handoff note (chosen) | Seamless, no user action needed, context preserved | LLM must reliably call the tool; adds tool to ReAct loop |
| Suggest + user @mentions | Simple, no new tool | Nicole can't act autonomously; user must remember to @mention |
| Automatic backend routing based on classification | No LLM tool call needed | Requires structured classification output; brittle |

- Positive: Nicole acts as a real dispatcher — she connects users to the right specialist.
- Positive: Handoff note preserves context, so the next agent starts informed.
- Positive: Frontend shows a visual handoff card, not raw tool output.
- Negative: LLM must reliably call bring_in with correct target; may need prompt tuning.
- Mitigation: Nicole's soul already instructs classification; bring_in is the natural action after classification. Validation rejects invalid targets (not in handoff_to).

